ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: A1: Impaired tolerance to certain stressors
A1.1: Impaired tolerance to unusual, unexpected or specific novel demands
A1.2: Impaired tolerance to certain social everyday situations
A1.3: Impaired tolerance to working under pressure of time or rapidly changing different demands
A2: Change in mood, emotional responsiveness
A2.1: Change in mood
A2.2: Change in emotional responsiveness
A3: Decrease in positive emotional responsiveness towards others
Affective-dynamic disturbances sum score (only 0-6 ratings)
B1: Inability to divide attention
B2: Feeling overly distracted by stimuli
B3: Difficulties concentrating
B4: Difficulties to hold things in mind for less than half an hour
B5: Slowed-down thinking
B6: Lack of thought energy, purposive thoughts
Cognitive-Attentional Impediments-sum score (only 0-6 ratings)
C1: Increased indecisiveness with regard to insignificant choices between equal alternatives
C2: Thought interference
C3: Thought blockages
C4: Disturbance of receptive speech
C5: Disturbance of expressive speech
C6: Disturbance of immediate recall
Cognitive Disturbances- sum score (only 0-6 ratings)
D1: Decreased capacity to discriminate between different kinds of emotions
D2: Increased emotional reactivity in response to routine social interactions
D3: Thought pressure
D4: Unstable ideas of reference
D5: Changed perception of the face or body of others
Disturbances in Experiencing the Self and Surroundings-sum score (only 0-6 ratings)
E1: Bodily sensations of numbness and stiffness
E2: Bodily sensations of pain in a distinct area
E3: Bodily sensations migrating through the body
E4: Bodily sensations of being electrified
E5: Bodily sensations of movement or pressure
E6: Bodily sensations of body/body parts changing size
Body Perception Disturbances-sum score (only 0-6 ratings)
F1: Hypersensitivity to light/optic stimuli
F2: Photopsia
F3: Micropsia, macropsia
F4: Hypersensitivity to sounds / noise
F5: Changed intensity/quality of acoustic stimuli
F6: Somatopsychic bodily depersonalization
Perception Disturbances- sum score (only 0-6 ratings)
O1: Thought perseveration
O2: Decreased ability to discriminate between ideas and perception, fantasy and true memories
O3: Disturbances of abstract thinking
O4: Other visual perception disturbances
O4.1: Near and tele-vision
O4.2: Metamorphopsia
O4.3: Changes in colour vision
O4.4: Changed perception of patients own face
O4.5: Pseudomovements of optic stimuli
O4.6: Diplopsia, oblique vision
O4.7: Disturbances of the estimation of distances or sizes
O4.8: Disturbances of the perception of straight lines/contours
O4.9: Maintenance of optic stimuli, visual echoes
O4.10: Partial seeing including tubular vision
O5: Other acoustic perception disturbances
O5.1: Acoasms
O5.2: Maintenance of acoustic stimuli, acoustic echoes
O6: Disturbances of olfactory, gustatory or tactile perception
O7: Captivation of attention by details of the visual field
O8: Derealization
O9: Motor interference exceeding simple lack of coordination
O10: Motor blockages
O11: Loss of automatic skills
COPER: 1. Have at least 1 of the symptoms listed? C2, C3, C4, D3, D4, O1, O2, O8, D5, F2, F3, O4.1-O4.10, F5, O5.1, O5.2
COPER: 2. If Yes to above question (coper 1), has any of these symptoms first occurred more than 12 months ago?
COPER: 3. If Yes to above questions (coper 1 and 2), are any of these symptoms with first occurrence more than 12 months ago scored at a "3-6" rating?
COPER: Yes to above questions (coper 1, 2, 3), COPER criteria met
COGDIS: 1. Have at least 2 of the symptoms listed been reported? B1, C5, O3, O7, C2, C3, C4, D3, and/or D4
COGDIS: 2. If Yes to the above question (coper 1), are at least 2 of these symptoms scored at a "3-6" rating?
COGDIS: Yes to 1 and 2? COGDIS criteria met.
Site
session ID/screening ID
Visit name
Subject Type
Data quality
Notes: 0=No data (cancelled); 1=Data entered but only once, has missing data; 2=Data entered but only once, no missing data; 3=Double entered; 4=Data frozen for cleaning; 5=Data clean/locked

ElementDescription: Checks for a pass/fail on Elig for Inclusion
Have the symptoms been present in the past 3 months
Are both B and C rated YES
Visit number
Sum of 9 item cognitive basic symptom criteria
